{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between CSV parsing (row-number tracking), schema validation, and DLQ publishing. A unit test of validator logic alone would miss off-by-one/mapping bugs in module interaction.","test_description":"Run the pipeline with a small CSV fixture containing known missing required fields at specific line numbers, wiring real parser+validator+DLQ writer modules (with local/in-memory sinks). Assert invalid rows are absent from normalized output and present in DLQ with exact original CSV row numbers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is core transformation/parsing logic in one boundary. Real I/O or cross-module wiring is not required to expose incorrect parsing/normalization.","test_description":"Table-driven unit tests for the date-normalization function with representative ISO 8601, US, and European inputs (including ambiguous dates), asserting exact canonical output and explicit failures for invalid values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Timeout and memory exhaustion are runtime/OS-level failure modes. Mocked components or narrow module tests can hide true throughput, buffering, GC, and memory-pressure behavior.